Using the function decideTests we classifies each t-statistic as significantly negative (down-regulation), not significant or significantly positive (up-regulation). If lfc>0 then contrasts are judged significant only when the log2-fold change is at least this large in absolute value. Moreover, we use adjust.method =âfdrâ (which is equal to âBHâ) because in microarray studies is more appropriate to control the false discovery rate instead of the family wise error rate, such as the Bonferroni correction. We show a little part of the differential expression results to explain how decideTests works to better understand the following upset plot. For each row, 1 means that that there is evidence that the gene is up-regulated for the considered contrast in the column, -1 means that there is evidence that the gene is down-regulated for the considered contrast, while 0 means there is no particular evidence of differential expression for the considered contrast. Upset plots are very useful to visualize the intersection between more than 3 sets. The total size of each set is represented on the left barplot. Every possible intersection is represented by the bottom plot, and their occurence is shown on the top barplot. Notably, the size of each contrast is calculated by aggregating all values for that specific contrast, which can result in a negative size if down-regulated genes outnumber up-regulated ones in that contrast. To account for both types of differential genes, we divide the negative values by the positive values and subsequently utilize an upset plot to visualize the outcomes.

genes_down = de_genes == -1
genes_up = de_genes == 1
colnames(genes_up) <- c(paste0("up", colnames(genes_up)))
colnames(genes_down) <- c(paste0("down", colnames(genes_down)))

mde_genes <- cbind(genes_up, genes_down)

mde_genes[mde_genes] <- 1

Let us explain briefly the process. edgeR stores data in a simple list-based data object called a DGEList. This type of object is easy to use because it can be manipulated like any list in R. The function readDGE makes a DGEList object directly. The main components of an DGEList object are a matrix counts containing the integer counts, a data.frame samples containing information about the samples or libraries, and a optional data.frame genes containing annotation for the genes or genomic features.

Since y is a DGEList object, calcNormFactors(y) returns the relative normalization factors in y\(samples\)norm.factors. The function estimateDisp calculates a matrix of likelihoods for each gene at a set of dispersion grid points, and then applies weighted likelihood empirical Bayes method to obtain posterior dispersion estimates.

Finally, glmFit fits a negative binomial generalized linear model to add an additional offset. The function glmLRT conducts likelihood ratio tests for one or more coefficients in the linear model. If the argument coef is used, the null hypothesis is that all the coefficients indicated by coef are equal to zero. Since we use coef=2, our H0 is that all the groupUntreated coefficients are equal to zero. The function topTags extracts the top DE genes (n=10 by default) in a data frame for a given pair of groups (here Treated and Untreated), ranked by p-value (default).

Now, we can insert some spot checks:

mds <- plotMDS(y, pch = 16, col = as.numeric(group), plot = FALSE)

df <- data.frame(MDS1 = mds$x, MDS2 = mds$y,
                 treatment = y$samples$group)

ggplot(df, aes(x = MDS1, y = MDS2, colour=treatment)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(color = "black", linewidth = 0.5, lineend = "square")
  ) +
  ggtitle("Multidimensional scaling plot of count from different samples")

plotBCV(y, col="darkgrey", col.common = "cyan", col.trend = "red")

Contrary to the microarray data, in counts data mean and variance are related. Since we use a negative binomial distribution model and we want to estimate the dispersion of each gene, so it is better to share information across genes exploiting the weighted likelihood. Since dispersion varies with mean, we moderate the dispersion towards the trend represented in the BCV plot.

de <- exactTest(y)
top_de_genes <- rownames(topTags(de, n=500)$table)
plotSmear(y, de.tags=top_de_genes)

We notice how, using a negative binomial distribution model, the MA plot keeps account for variation even when the average logCPM is big, where the Poisson distribution model would not. The red dots are the most differentially expressed genes.

Question 4

For the MDS plot, investigate what happens differently when you call plotMDS() on the DGEList object and when you call it on the normalized counts â for normalized counts, see the cpm() function. Explain why it is different. You may need to read the documentation or even read the code of the plotMDS.DGEList or plotMDS.default functions to understand the difference.

The different behaviour of plotMDS with a matrix/array and a DGEList relies on the different normalization method. In fact, plotMDS.DGEList converts the counts to log-counts-per-milion using cpm with the argument log=TRUE. After this step, plotMDS.DGEList will pass the log-counts-per-milion to the default function plotMDS. On the contrary, when we call the function cpm(y), the argument log=FALSE by default. Hence, CPM values are not retunred on the log scale when we manually normalize them. Therefore, the different mda coordinates are due to the log transformation, occuring thanks to the argument log=TRUE inside the cpm call only in plotMDS.DGEList.

If we compare the two different normalization on the same MDS plot:

mds <- plotMDS(y, plot = FALSE)
counts_norm = cpm(counts)
mds_norm <- plotMDS(counts_norm, plot = FALSE)

mds_df <- data.frame(MDS1 = mds$x, MDS2 = mds$y,
                 treatment = grp, method = "DGEList object")

mds_df_norm <- data.frame(MDS1 = mds_norm$x, MDS2 = mds_norm$y,
                 treatment = grp, method = "normalized counts")

total_df = rbind(mds_df, mds_df_norm)

ggplot(total_df, aes(x = MDS1, y = MDS2, color = treatment, shape = method)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  theme_bw() +
    theme(
      panel.border = element_blank(),
      axis.line = element_line(color = "black", linewidth = 0.5, lineend = "square")
    ) +
  ggtitle("Comparison of the function plotMDS with different objects (log=FALSE)")

we can see that the log-CPM obtained from the DGEList are all very close to each others, because the CPM obtained from the normalized counts are on another scale such that we cannot distinguish the log-CPM. We can have a better visualization of the log-CPM in the MDS plot of point 3.

Finally, we can show that if we insert the argument log=TRUE when manually normalizing the counts, the two results on the MDS plot are comparable:

mds <- plotMDS(y, plot = FALSE)
counts_norm = cpm(counts, log=TRUE)
mds_norm <- plotMDS(counts_norm, plot = FALSE)

mds_df <- data.frame(MDS1 = mds$x, MDS2 = mds$y,
                 treatment = grp, method = "DGEList object")

mds_df_norm <- data.frame(MDS1 = mds_norm$x, MDS2 = mds_norm$y,
                 treatment = grp, method = "normalized counts")

total_df = rbind(mds_df, mds_df_norm)

ggplot(total_df, aes(x = MDS1, y = MDS2, color = treatment, shape = method)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  theme_bw() +
    theme(
      panel.border = element_blank(),
      axis.line = element_line(color = "black", linewidth = 0.5, lineend = "square")
    ) +
  ggtitle("Comparison of the function plotMDS with different objects (log=TRUE)")

Question 5

Again, the above code for voom is not run here. Fix this code to work with the count dataset above and then do some spot checks of the genes called DE. For example, make a plot of the estimated fold changes for the two methods (limma-voom and edgeR), compare the P-values of the two methods, or create a venn diagram of the called sets of DE genes at a set threshold.

v <- voom(y$counts, design=model.matrix(~grp), plot = TRUE)

vf = lmFit(v, design = model.matrix(~grp))  # note similarity to limma
                                            # analysis performed earlier
vf = eBayes(vf)

In the voom function, counts are transformed to log2 counts per million reads (CPM), where âper million readsâ is defined based on the normalization factors we calculated earlier in the function calcNormFactors. This is done because since we want to use the Limma pipeline, calculating the logCPM flattens a little bit the relation between dispersion and mean in the genes. If this transformation is not enough, one can drop the genes that confer a slope to the curve. The following is just an example:

cutoff <- 5
drop <- which(apply(cpm(y), 1, max) < cutoff)
y_drop <- y[-drop,] 

v_drop <- voom(y_drop$counts, design=model.matrix(~grp), plot = TRUE)

vf_drop = lmFit(v_drop, design = model.matrix(~grp))
vf_drop = eBayes(vf_drop)

After having transformed the counts, a linear model is fitted to the log2 CPM for each gene, and the residuals are calculated. Then, a smoothed curve is fitted to the sqrt(residual standard deviation) by average expression (see red line in plot above). Finally, the smoothed curve (which now should be flat enough) is used to obtain weights for each gene and sample that are passed into limma along with the log2 CPMs.

Now we can do some spot checks, but first we have to find the 10 genes selected by the edgeR pipeline in the limma results and sort the two results tables with the same order:

limma_results <- topTable(vf, n=Inf)

From this scatterplot, we see how two different strategies can come up with very similar results. In fact, when dealing with count data, you can decide either to analyze this data with models specifically developed for count data (e.g.Â edgeR), or to transfrom the count data to normally-distributed data and then apply some very well-developed normal distribution models (e.g.Â voom + Limma). At the end, both methods are effective in this case.

We can now compare the p-values. We notice from the beginning they are different because they were produced from two different methods, so we can make a scatterplot to see if they are correlated:

p_values <- data.frame(Limma = limma_results$P.Value,
                      edgeR = edgeR_results$PValue)
                       
ggplot(logFC, aes(x = -log(Limma), y = -log(edgeR))) +
  geom_point(color = "lightblue") +
  theme_bw() +
    theme(
      panel.border = element_blank(),
      axis.line = element_line(color = "black", linewidth = 0.5, lineend = "square")
    ) +

As we presumed, the p-values obtained from the two methods are correlated. They are different just because they are produced by two different statistical methods.
